english:
  title: An Explanation of 'Nae-Ong' Upon Sending Off Pae Yun-gyeon on His Return Eastward
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have known Nae-ong for a long time. In my earlier years, I passed the national examination and, as was customary, went out to serve as a clerk-administrator. When I returned after completing my term, Nae-ong was still a student. Among the students, he was somewhat older in years and superior in talent, so all the students respected and followed him. By nature he loved wine, and if he went even a single day without it, he seemed to have lost something precious. For this reason, the other students delighted in his company, and I too would often join them. I came to know that his heart harbored no duplicity.

    Later, I passed the provincial examination and took up an official post in the Middle Kingdom, so we were separated for a long time. In the year Ding-chou of the Zhiyuan era, I came out to serve in the provincial administration, and by then Nae-ong had already passed the imperial examinations of the Middle Kingdom, his reputation rising ever higher. Yet his character remained unchanged from his student days, and I came to appreciate his genuine simplicity all the more. Now I find myself again in the capital, and when the home country dispatched an envoy to celebrate the imperial birthday, Nae-ong was selected for his literary skill to present the memorial at court. At that time the imperial procession had already passed through the mountain barriers. Nae-ong traveled northward with the embassy, weathering hardships along the way, was received in the imperial tent, and proceeded all the way to Luan-jing. After dwelling there for several months, he returned to Yan-du and remained there for several more months. Again I kept company with him, and Nae-ong remained as he had always been. Though all the other envoys had departed, he alone stayed behind, and it has now been several months more.

    Yesterday he came to me and said: "A few nights past, I dreamed my parents waited at the threshold. When I departed, I did not tell them of my intention to linger long in these lands. I must return and obey their wishes. Whether I shall come again, I cannot say. Would you not compose some words to bid me farewell? Moreover, my form is bent while my stature is tall, and people call me Nae-ong—the Old One. I have accepted this name, yet 'nae' is merely a particle of speech, and people, not knowing this, think it meaningless. Should you not provide an explanation?"

    Since I have long known Nae-ong, I readily replied: "I shall do so. All names and appellations, whether given by others or chosen by oneself, carry meaning. When others bestow a name, they offer something fine; when one chooses one's own, there lies humility. Through such humility comes wisdom—not foolishness but depth, not clumsiness but subtlety. Yet names arise from reality; if the reality holds true, even an unfavorable title cannot be refused. This is like trying to cover something that cannot be hidden.

    Once in ancient Qi, a farmer kept cattle. His cow bore a calf. Taking the calf to market, he traded it for a horse. A young man protested: 'Cows do not bear horses!' and carried off the horse. The neighbors called the farmer foolish—a simple man—yet he did not contest their words. Perhaps he understood something they did not.

    Consider how characters were first formed: combining 'one' and 'great' yields 'heaven'; 'earth' combines 'soil' and 'also'; 'trust' joins 'person' and 'speech'; 'anger' unites 'slave' and 'heart.' By such principles we may understand all. Yet the ancients had much they did not fully know. Characters were created to represent things; things were not created because characters exist for them. Thus few things resemble their characters. Creatures born in later ages may have no character to represent them. How much less can the forms of people and objects be perfectly matched to the dots and strokes of written signs?

    Yet we do call a river that resembles a character by its written shape; why should we fault calling a man who resembles a character by his resemblance? Moreover, 'nae' as a particle is not without meaning—it serves a purpose. Without particles, writing cannot be writing, just as without weft, there can be no patterned silk. Furthermore, the character itself teaches restraint: it means 'difficult' or 'rare,' suggesting that one should not speak lightly. When others address us informally, and we receive it gracefully, this too is the way of the humble.

    When the envoys of Wu and Shu insulted each other through their state titles, or when the families of Xie and Shi slandered one another through their surnames, they were playing games with characters. But of Nae-ong, I would never speak so."
  footnotes:
    - 'Nae-ong (乃翁): Literally ''the old one''—a playful epithet referring to Pae Yun-gyeon''s distinctive physical appearance: his hunched posture combined with his height made him resemble the character 乃 (nae) or 翁 (ong, meaning old man).'
    - 'Luan-jing (灤京): A temporary capital used by the Yuan court during its northern tours.'
    - 'The tale of the Qi farmer: A classical parable illustrating how appearance can deceive, and how the farmer''s dignified silence in the face of mockery suggests deeper wisdom than those who judged him possessed.'
    - 'Wu and Shu: Ancient states whose envoys famously quarreled over the proper titles for their respective nations, using written characters as weapons of insult.'
